// TEST: stdlib_convert_output_smoke
// EXPECT: output "out of range"
//
// A `main` that builds a `ConvertError` via the `core.convert.convert_error`
// constructor and prints its `message`. The constructor body runs through the
// embedded `core.convert` module cross-module.
//
// NOTE: the harness currently *parses* `// EXPECT: output` directives but does
// not yet execute fixtures (cross-target execution is staged for the Q-fconf
// task). Until then this fixture is validated by loading (no LoadError) and by
// the CLI-level `bock run` smoke in bock-cli's `stdlib_convert` integration
// suite, which asserts this exact "out of range" output against the real
// interpreter.
//
// The smoke deliberately exercises the free `convert_error` constructor and a
// field access rather than a conversion trait method: at run time the
// interpreter cannot dispatch `Type.from(x)` (user associated functions), the
// derived blanket `Into.into` (no method body), or `Displayable.to_string`
// (shadowed by the universal record `to_string` builtin) — type-checking and
// codegen handle all three. See the session PR notes.
module main

use core.convert.{convert_error}

public fn main() {
  println(convert_error("out of range").message)
}
